Introduction¶

This report analyzes a dataset of medical appointments in Brazil. In particular we will be looking trends amongst likelihood of patients who showed up for their scheduled appointments, and how they differed from patients who did not show up.

Data Cleaning¶

Notes on the data:

  1. There are 110527 rows and 15 columns of data.
  2. No missing values or duplicates were found.
  3. There are values of "-1" and "0" for "Age" column. Clarification with dataset creator indicates that negative values were for patients who were pregnant and the age is age of the child.
  4. Values for the "Handcap" column range from 1 to 4 indicating the number of disabilities the person has.
  5. "No show" column is a little confusing with "No" indicating that the patient showed up and the reverse for "Yes"
  6. "ScheduledDay" indicates the date the appointment is made while "AppointmentDay" is the date of the appointment itself.
  7. "AppointmentDay" and "ScheduledDay" Columns are string variables instead of date time variables and will need to be converted for further analysis.

Step 1: Calculating difference between the day the appointment day and scheduled day.¶

One key variable to which will likely differ between patient who show up is the time between the appointments. The following data cleaning calculates the difference between the two, and adds a "DaysDifference" column, and a "DayDiffBin" column to classify the time frames

In [480]:
#Creating column to which calculated the difference between the appointment day and the day the appointment is scheduled.
#Converting "ScheduledDay" and "AppointmentDay" columns to datetime format

df['ScheduledDay'] = pd.to_datetime(df['ScheduledDay'])
df['AppointmentDay'] = pd.to_datetime(df['AppointmentDay'])

# Calculating difference between appointment day and scheduled day, rounding to "days" and converting it to dtype float for further analysis
DaysDifference = (df['AppointmentDay'] - df['ScheduledDay'])
DaysDifferenceFloat = (DaysDifference.dt.round('d'))
df["DaysDifference"] = DaysDifferenceFloat
df["DaysDifference"] = df["DaysDifference"].dt.days.astype(float)

# Around 10% of the days difference values were <0. Opted to drop values as remaining dataset is still farily large

In [482]:
#Creating bin edges and bin names for difference
#Bin edges chosen were 0 to 15 days (half a month, 15 to 30 days (1 month), 30 days to 90 days (3 months), and > 90 days  
bin_edges = [0,15,30,90,179]
bin_names = ["0 to 15 days","15 to 30 days","30 to 90 days","> 90 days "]
In [483]:
#Creating DayDiffBin column
df['DayDiffBin'] = pd.cut(df['DaysDifference'],bin_edges, labels = bin_names, include_lowest = True)

Step 2: Converting "No Show" Column for easier analysis and more intuitive understanding.¶

Currently, the "No-show" column is a little confusing with "No" indicating that the patient showed up and the reverse for "Yes". The following steps replace "No" with "1", "Yes" with "0", and crenames the column to "ShowedUp"

In [485]:
# Replacing "No" with "1", "Yes" with "0"
df["No-show"].replace({"No": 1, "Yes": 0}, inplace = True)
In [486]:
# Renaming "No-show" column
df.rename(columns = {"No-show" : "TurnedUp"}, inplace = True)

While the following neighbourhoods have the higher rate of turning up:

def autolabel_ax2(rects):
    for rect in rects:
        width, height = rect.get_width(), rect.get_height()
        x , y = rect.get_xy()
        ax2.annotate('{:.2f}%'.format(width),
                    xy = (x + width / 2, y + height/2),
                    ha='center', va='center',                    
                    )
        
autolabel_ax2(neighbourhood_bar)
fig2.tight_layout()

Research Question 3: Is a greater difference in between the scheduled day and appointment day associated with a higher rate of no shows?¶

A higher difference between the scheduled day and appointment day is associated with a higher rate of no shows, except for the >90 days group which has a lower rate of no shows than the 15 to 30 days group, and the 30 days to 90 days group.

# Setting up data for stacked bar plot

DayLabels = bin_names 
TurnedUp_mean = (100*(df.groupby("DayDiffBin")["TurnedUp"].mean())).round(2)
NoShow_mean = (100*(1 - df.groupby("DayDiffBin")["TurnedUp"].mean())).round(2)

# Plot parameters
x = 1 * (np.arange(len(TurnedUp_mean)))
width = 0.5

fig3, ax3 = plt.subplots(figsize = (15,8))

TurnedUp_bar = ax3.bar(x, TurnedUp_mean, width=width, label = "Turned Up")
NoShow_bar = ax3.bar(x, NoShow_mean, width=width, label = "No Show", bottom =TurnedUp_mean)

#Adding labels

ax3.set_ylabel("Percentage (%)");
ax3.set_title("Split of Patients who Turned Up vs No Shows, by Period of Time between Scheduling and Appointment")
ax3.set_xticks(x)
ax3.set_xticklabels(DayLabels)
ax3.legend( loc = 1)


def autolabel_ax3(rects):
    for rect in rects:
        width, height = rect.get_width(), rect.get_height()
        x , y = rect.get_xy()
        ax3.annotate('{:.2f}%'.format(height),
                    xy = (x + width / 2, y + height/2),
                    ha='center', va='center',                    
                    )

        
autolabel_ax3(TurnedUp_bar)
autolabel_ax3(NoShow_bar)
fig3.tight_layout()

Research Question 4: Is receiving a SMS reminder associated with a higher rate of turning up?¶

Counterintuitively, it seems as it more of those who did not receive an SMS turned up for their appointments.

In [500]:
# Checking whether more of those who received an SMS turned up
df.groupby("SMS_received")["TurnedUp"].mean()
Out[500]:
SMS_received
0    0.810190
1    0.724255
Name: TurnedUp, dtype: float64

The higher rate of turning up for those who did not receive an SMS could be due to the appointments with short period between the day they made the appointment and the appointment itself not being sent an SMS (e.g. appointments made on the same day of the appointment would not need an SMS reminder). This is especially important as there is a large number of patients who have a "DaysDifference" of 0

def autolabel_ax4(rects):

Conclusions¶

In this analysis we posed 4 research questions :

  1. What is the percentage of no-shows?
  2. Which neighbourhoods have the highest and lowest rate of turning up?
  3. Is a greater difference in between the scheduled day and appointment day associated with a higher rate of no shows?
  4. Is receiving a SMS reminder associated with a higher rate of turning up?

1. What is the percentage of no-shows?¶

We found that around 78% of appointments showed up

2. Which neighbourhoods have the highest and lowest rate of turning up?¶

After excluding neighbourhoods with too few datapoints, the following neighbourhoods have the lowest rate of turning up. Patients from these neighbourhoods could be studied further to understand if there are any underlying or systemic factors that affect their ability to turn up and thus develop appropriate assistance or interventions for this group:

  1. SANTOS DUMONT
  2. SANTA CECÍLIA
  3. SANTA CLARA
  4. ITARARÉ
  5. ILHA DO PRÍNCIPE

The following have the highest rate of turning up. This group could be studied further to see if there any commonalities/best practices which could be adopted for the former group:

  1. SOLON BORGES
  2. DO CABRAL
  3. DE LOURDES
  4. MORADA DE CAMBURI
  5. MÁRIO CYPRESTE

3. Is a greater difference in between the scheduled day and appointment day associated with a higher rate of no shows?¶

Except for appointments which were scheduled >90 days before the appointment date, a greater difference between the scheduled day and appointment day is associated with a higher rate of no shows with the 0 to 15 day group have the least no shows at 18.3%, followed by the 15 to 30 day group at 32.5% and 30 to 90 day group at 33.1%

The >90 day group had 27.4% rate of no shows, lower rate than the 15 to 30 day and 30 to 90 day groups. This could be for several reasons such as the type of appointment (e.g regular 6 month check ups vs appointments for ad-hoc conditions) and would warrant further investigation.

In [508]:
fig3
Out[508]:

4. Is receiving an SMS reminder associated with a higher rate of turning up?¶

For this analysis, we dropped cases which had < 2 days difference between the scheduled day and appointment day as these appointments did not receive an SMS reminder.

For all groups, except the > 90 days group, patients who received an SMS reminder turned up for their appointments at a higher rate, with the 15 to 30 day and 30 to 90 day group seeing ~7% higher turn up rate if they received a reminder. The effect was less pronounced for the 2 to 15 day group which had ~2.5% higher turn up rate for the group that received a reminder.
